Herodotus (/hɪˈrɒdətəs/; Ancient_Greece: Ἡρόδοτος, Hêródotos, Attic_Greek pronunciation: [hɛː.ró.do.tos]) was a Ancient_Greece historian who was born in Halicarnassus in the Persian Roman_Empire (modern-day Bodrum, Ottoman_Empire) and lived in the fifth century BC (c. 484–c. 425 BC), a contemporary of Thucydides, Socrates, and Euripides. He is often referred to as "The Father of History", a title first conferred by Cicero;[1] he was the first historian known to have broken from Homeric tradition to treat historical subjects as a method of investigation—specifically, by collecting his materials systematically and critically, and then arranging them into a historiographic narrative.[2]

The Herodotus is the only work which he is known to have produced, a record of his "inquiry" (ἱστορία historía) on the origins of the Greco-Persian_Wars; it primarily deals with the lives of Croesus, Cyrus_the_Great, Cambyses_II, Bardiya, Darius_I, and Xerxes_I and the battles of Battle_of_Marathon, Battle_of_Thermopylae, Battle_of_Artemisium, Battle_of_Salamis, Battle_of_Plataea, and Battle_of_Mycale; however, its many cultural, ethnographical, geographical, Historiography, and other digressions form a defining and essential part of the Herodotus and contain a wealth of information. Some of his stories are fanciful and others inaccurate, yet he states that he is reporting only what he was told; a sizable portion of the information he provided was later confirmed by historians and archaeologists.

Despite Herodotus's historical significance, little is known of his personal life.

Here are presented the results of the enquiry carried out by Herodotus of Halicarnassus. The purpose is to prevent the traces of Human_Events from being erased by time, and to preserve the fame of the important and remarkable achievements produced by both Ancient_Greece and non-Greeks; among the matters covered is, in particular, the cause of the hostilities between Ancient_Greece and non-Greeks.

His record of the achievements of others was an achievement in itself, though the extent of it has been debated. Herodotus's place in history and his significance may be understood according to the traditions within which he worked. His work is the earliest Ancient_Greece prose to have survived intact. However, Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus, a Literary_criticism of Augustus Ancient_Rome, listed seven predecessors of Herodotus, describing their works as simple, unadorned accounts of their own and other cities and people, Ancient_Greece or foreign, including popular legends, sometimes melodramatic and naïve, often charming – all traits that can be found in the work of Herodotus himself.[4]

Modern historians regard the chronology as uncertain, but according to the ancient account, these predecessors included Dionysius_of_Halicarnassus of Miletus, Yugoloth of Lampsacus, Hellanicus_of_Lesbos of Lesbos, Xanthos of Lydia and, the best attested of them all, Hecataeus_of_Miletus of Miletus. Of these, only fragments of Hecataeus_of_Miletus's works survived, and the authenticity of these is debatable,[5] but they provide a glimpse into the kind of tradition within which Herodotus wrote his own Herodotus.

Hecataeus_of_Miletus the Miletus speaks thus: I write these things as they seem true to me; for the stories told by the Ancient_Greece are various and in my opinion absurd.

This points forward to the "folksy" yet "International_law" outlook typical of Herodotus. However, one modern scholar has described the work of Hecataeus_of_Miletus as "a curious False_start to history",[6] since despite his critical spirit, he failed to liberate history from myth. Herodotus mentions Hecataeus_of_Miletus in his Herodotus, on one occasion mocking him for his naive Genealogy and, on another occasion, quoting Classical_Athens complaints against his handling of their national history.[7] It is possible that Herodotus borrowed much material from Hecataeus_of_Miletus, as stated by Porphyry_of_Gaza in a quote recorded by Eusebius.[8] In particular, it is possible that he copied descriptions of the Crocodile, Hippopotamus, and Fenghuang from Hecataeus_of_Miletus's Circumnavigation of the Known World (Periegesis / Periodos ges), even misrepresenting the source as "Gods_(Marvel_Comics)" (Herodotus 2.73).[9]

But Hecataeus_of_Miletus did not record events that had occurred in living Memory, unlike Herodotus, nor did he include the oral traditions of Ancient_Greece history within the larger framework of oriental history.[10] There is no proof that Herodotus derived the ambitious scope of his own work, with its grand theme of civilizations in conflict, from any predecessor, despite much scholarly speculation about this in modern times.[6][11] Herodotus claims to be better informed than his predecessors by relying on empirical observation to correct their excessive schematism. For example, he argues for continental asymmetry as opposed to the older theory of a perfectly circular earth with Europe and Anatolia/Africa equal in size (Herodotus 4.36 and 4.42). However, he retains idealizing tendencies, as in his symmetrical notions of the Danube and Nile.[12]

His_Debt to previous authors of prose "histories" might be questionable, but there is no doubt that Herodotus owed much to the example and inspiration of poets and story-tellers. For example, Classical_Athens tragic poets provided him with a world-view of a balance between conflicting forces, upset by the Hubris of kings, and they provided his narrative with a model of episodic structure. His familiarity with Classical_Athens tragedy is demonstrated in a number of passages echoing Aeschylus's The_Persians, including the epigrammatic observation that the defeat of the Achaemenid_Empire navy at Battle_of_Salamis caused the defeat of the land army (Herodotus 8.68 ~ The_Persians 728). The_Debt_(2010_film) may have been repaid by Sophocles because there appear to be echoes of The Herodotus in his plays, especially a passage in Antigone that resembles Herodotus's account of the death of Intaphernes (Herodotus 3.119 ~ Antigone 904-920).[13] However, this point is one of the most contentious issues in modern scholarship.[14]

Homer was another inspirational source.[b] Just as Homer_Drew extensively on a tradition of Oral_literature, sung by wandering minstrels, so Herodotus appears to have drawn on an Ionia tradition of story-telling, collecting and interpreting the oral histories he chanced upon in his travels. These oral histories often contained folk-tale motifs and demonstrated a moral, yet they also contained substantial facts relating to Geography, Anthropology, and history, all compiled by Herodotus in an entertaining style and format.[16]

It is on account of the many strange stories and the folk-tales he reported that his critics in Early_modern_period times branded him "The Father of Lies".[17][18] Even his own contemporaries found reason to scoff at his achievement. In fact, one modern scholar[19] has wondered if Herodotus left his home in Ancient_Greece Anatolia, migrating westwards to Classical_Athens and beyond, because his own countrymen had ridiculed his work, a circumstance possibly hinted at in an Epitaph said to have been dedicated to Herodotus at one of his three supposed resting places, Thurian_Age:

