lies; in Ionia history without peer; 
a Dorians born, who fled from Defamation's brand 
and made in Thurian_Age his new native land.[20]

Yet it was in Classical_Athens where his most Formidable-class_frigate contemporary critics could be found. In 425 BC, which is about the time that Herodotus is thought by many scholars to have died, the Classical_Athens comic Theatre_of_ancient_Greece Aristophanes created The_Acharnians, in which he blames the Peloponnesian_War on the abduction of some prostitutes – a mocking reference to Herodotus, who reported the Achaemenid_Empire' account of their wars with Ancient_Greece, beginning with the rapes of the mythical heroines List_of_locations_in_Babylon_5, Europa_F.C., Medea, and Helen.[21][22]

Similarly, the Classical_Athens historian Thucydides dismissed Herodotus as a "logos-writer" (story-teller).[23] Thucydides, who had been trained in Rhetoric, became the model for subsequent prose-writers as an author who seeks to appear firmly in control of his material, whereas with his frequent digressions Herodotus appeared to minimize (or possibly disguise) his authorial control.[24] Moreover, Thucydides developed a historical topic more in keeping with the Ancient_Greece world-view: focused on the context of the polis or Polis. The Interplay_Entertainment of civilizations was more relevant to Ancient_Greece living in Anatolia, such as Herodotus himself, for whom life within a foreign civilization was a recent Memory.[23]

Before the Achaemenid_Empire crisis, history had been represented among the Ancient_Greece only by local or family traditions. The "Wars of Liberation" had given to Herodotus the first genuinely historical inspiration felt by a Ancient_Greece. These wars showed him that there was a corporate life, higher than that of the City, of which the story might be told; and they offered to him as a subject the drama of the collision between East and West. With him, the spirit of history was born into Ancient_Greece; and his work, called after the nine Muse, was indeed the first utterance of Clio.

