Herodotus wrote his Herodotus in the Ionia Dialect, yet he was born in Halicarnassus, which was a Dorians settlement. According to the Suda, Herodotus learned the Ionia Dialect as a boy living on the island of Samos, to which he had fled with his family from the oppressions of Tugdamme, Tyrant of Halicarnassus and grandson of Artemisia_I_of_Caria I. The Suda also Institute_for_Operations_Research_and_the_Management_Sciences us that Herodotus later returned home to lead the revolt that eventually overthrew the Tyrant. Due to recent discoveries of inscriptions at Halicarnassus dated to about Herodotus's time, we now know that the Ionic_Greek was used in Halicarnassus in some official documents, so there is no need to assume (like the Suda) that he must have learned the Dialect elsewhere.[32] Further, the Suda is the only source which we have for the role played by Herodotus as the heroic liberator of his birthplace. That itself is a good reason to doubt such a romantic account.[33]

As Herodotus himself reveals, Halicarnassus, though a Dorians City, had ended its Close_Relations with its Dorians neighbours after an unseemly quarrel (I, 144), and it had helped pioneer Ancient_Greece trade with Ancient_Egypt (II, 178). It was, therefore, an outward-looking, international-minded port within the Persian Roman_Empire, and the historian's family could well have had contacts in other countries under Achaemenid_Empire rule, facilitating his travels and his researches.

Herodotus's eye-witness accounts indicate that he traveled in Ancient_Egypt in association with Athenians, probably some time after 454 BC or possibly earlier, after an Classical_Athens fleet had assisted the uprising against Achaemenid_Empire rule in 460–454 BC. He probably traveled to Tire next and then down the Euphrates to Babylon. For some reason, possibly associated with local politics, he subsequently found himself unpopular in Halicarnassus, and some time around 447 BC, migrated to Periclean Classical_Athens – a City whose people and democratic institutions he openly admires (V, 78). Classical_Athens was also the place where he came to know the local topography (VI, 137; VIII, 52–5), as well as leading citizens such as the Alcmaeonidae, a Clan whose history features frequently in his writing.

According to Eusebius[34] and Plutarch,[35] Herodotus was granted a financial reward by the Athenian_democracy in recognition of his work. It is possible that he unsuccessfully applied for Classical_Athens citizenship, a rare honour after 451 BC, requiring two separate votes by a well-attended assembly.

In 443 BC or shortly afterwards, he migrated to Thurii as part of an Athenian-sponsored Colonies_in_antiquity. Aristotle refers to a version of The Herodotus written by "Herodotus of Thurii", and some passages in the Herodotus have been interpreted as proof that he wrote about southern Roman_Italy from personal experience there (IV, 15,99; VI, 127). Intimate knowledge of some events in the first years of the Peloponnesian_War (VI, 91; VII, 133, 233; Final_Fantasy_IX, 73) indicate that he might have returned to Classical_Athens, in which case it is possible that he died there during an outbreak of the Bubonic_plague. Possibly he died in Republic_of_Macedonia instead, after obtaining the patronage of the court there; or else he died back in Thurii. There is nothing in the Herodotus that can be dated to later than 430 BC with any certainty, and it is generally assumed that he died not long afterwards, possibly before his 60th_United_States_Congress year.

Herodotus would have made his researches known to the larger world through oral recitations to a public crowd. John Marincola writes in his introduction to the Penguin edition of The Herodotus that there are certain identifiable pieces in the early books of Herodotus's work which could be labeled as "performance pieces". These portions of the research seem independent and "almost detachable", so that they might have been set aside by the author for the purposes of an oral performance. The intellectual Composite_material of the 5th century, Marincola suggests, comprised many oral performances in which philosophers would dramatically recite such detachable pieces of their work. The idea was to criticize previous arguments on a topic and emphatically and enthusiastically insert their own in order to win over the audience.[36]

It was conventional in Herodotus's day for authors to "publish" their works by reciting them at popular festivals. According to Lucian, Herodotus took his finished work straight from Anatolia to the Ancient_Olympic_Games and read the entire Herodotus to the assembled spectators in one sitting, receiving rapturous applause at the end of it.[37] According to a very different account by an ancient Grammar,[38] Herodotus refused to begin reading his work at the festival of Opel_Olympia until some clouds offered him a bit of shade – by which time the assembly had dispersed. (Hence the proverbial Idiom "Herodotus and his shade" to describe someone who misses an opportunity through delay.) Herodotus's recitation at Opel_Olympia was a favourite theme among ancient writers, and there is another interesting variation on the story to be found in the Suda: that of Photios_I_of_Constantinople[39] and Tzetzes,[40] in which a young Thucydides happened to be in the assembly with his father, and burst into tears during the recital. Herodotus observed prophetically to the boy's father, "Your son's Soul yearns for knowledge."

Eventually, Thucydides and Herodotus became close enough for both to be interred in Thucydides' tomb in Classical_Athens. Such at least was the opinion of Marcellinus in his Life of Thucydides.[41] According to the Suda, he was buried in Ancient_Macedonians Pella and in the Agora in Thurii.[42]

The Herodotus were occasionally criticized in Ancient_Greece,[c] but modern historians and philosophers generally take a positive view.[43] Despite the controversy,[44][d] Herodotus still serves as the primary, and often only, source for events in the Ancient_Greece world, Persian Roman_Empire, and the region generally in the two centuries leading up until his own day.[17][46] Herodotus, like many ancient historians, preferred an element of show[e] to purely analytic history, aiming to give pleasure with "exciting events, great dramas, bizarre Exotica."[48] As such, certain passages[49][50] have been the subject of controversy and even some doubt, both in Ancient_Greece and today.[51][52][53][54][55][56][57][f]

The accuracy of the works of Herodotus has been controversial since his own era.[g] Cicero[h][59] Aristotle, Josephus, Duris of Samos,[i][60] Harpocration[j][61] and Plutarch all commented on this controversy.[62][63] Generally, however, he was regarded as reliable in Ancient_Greece, and is especially so today. Many scholars, ancient and modern, routinely cite Herodotus (e.g., Aubin_Codex, A. H. L. Heeren, Alan_Davidson_(cricketer,_born_1929), Sheikh Tapir Diop, Edgar_Allan_Poe, Welsby,_Queensland, Celenko, Constantin_François_de_Chassebœuf,_comte_de_Volney, Pierre_Montet, Bernal, Jackson_Guitars, DuBois, Strabo). Many of these scholars (Welsby,_Queensland, Heeren, Aubin_Codex, Diop, etc.) explicitly mention the reliability of Herodotus's work[k] and demonstrate corroboration of Herodotus's writings by modern scholars.[l][64] A. H. L. Heeren quoted Herodotus throughout his work and provided corroboration by scholars regarding several passages (source of the Nile, location of Meroe, etc.).[65] To further his work on the Ancient_Egypt and Assyria, Aubin_Codex uses Herodotus's accounts in various passages and defends Herodotus's position. Aubin_Codex said that Herodotus was "the author of the first important narrative history of the world".[66] Diop provides several examples (the inundations of the Nile) which, he argues, support his view that Herodotus was "quite scrupulous, objective, scientific for his time." Diop argues that Herodotus "always distinguishes carefully between what he has seen and what he has been told." Diop also notes that Strabo corroborated Herodotus's ideas about the Black_Sea Ancient_Egypt, Ethiopians, and Colchis.[67][68]

The reliability of Herodotus' writing about Ancient_Egypt is sometimes criticized.[57][m] Alan B. Lloyd argues that, as a historical document, the writings of Herodotus are seriously defective, and that he was working from "inadequate sources".[51] Nielsen_ratings writes: "Though we cannot entirely rule out the possibility of Herodotus having been in Ancient_Egypt, it must be said that his narrative bears little witness to it."[52] German historian Detlev Fehling questions whether Herodotus ever traveled up the Nile River, and considers doubtful almost everything that he says about Ancient_Egypt and Aethiopia.[69][53] Fehling states that "there is not the slightest bit of history behind the whole story" about the claim of Herodotus that Pharaoh Sesostris campaigned in Europe, and that he left a Colonies_in_antiquity in Colchia.[55][54][n]

Herodotus provides much information about the nature of the world and the status of science during his lifetime, often engaging in private speculation. For example, he reports that the annual flooding of the Nile was said to be the result of melting snows far to the south, and he comments that he cannot understand how there can be Snow in Africa, the hottest part of the known world, offering an elaborate explanation based on the way that Desert_Winds affect the passage of the Ra over this part of the world (2:18ff). He also passes on reports from Phoenicia sailors that, while circumnavigating Africa, they "saw the sun on the right side while sailing westwards". Owing to this brief mention, which is included almost as an afterthought, it has been argued that Africa was circumnavigated by ancient seafarers, for this is precisely where the sun ought to have been. His accounts of History_of_India are among the oldest records of Indian civilization by an outsider.[70][71][72]

Discoveries made since the end of the 19th century have generally added to Herodotus's credibility. He described Gelonus, located in Scythia, as a City thousands of times larger than Troy; this was widely disbelieved until it was rediscovered in 1975. The archaeological study of the now-submerged ancient Ancient_Egypt City of Heracleion and the recovery of the so-called "Naucratis Stele" give credibility to Herodotus's previously unsupported claim that Heracleion was founded during the Ancient_Egypt New_Kingdom_of_Egypt.

